05819nam a22009375i 9781487530310DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875303107 a10.3138/97814875303102doi  a(DE-B1597)536652  a(OCoLC)1113866062  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR468.A66bW37 2019 7aLIT0240302bisacsh04a820.9/1452231 aWashington, Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRomantic Revelations :bVisions of Post-Apocalyptic Life and Hope in the Anthropocene /cChris Washington. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: There Is a Light That Never Goes Out? -- t1. The Mind Is Its Own Place: What Percy Shelley’s Mountain Did Not Say -- t2. No More Cakes and Ale, Only Oil Slicks: Mary Shelley’s Post-Apocalyptic State of Nature -- t3. Byron’s Speculative Turn: The Biopolitics of Paradise -- t4. Birds Do It, Bees Do It: John Clare, Biopolitics, and the Nonhuman Origins of Love -- t5. The Best of All Possible End of the Worlds: Jane Austen’s Frankenstein, or Love in the Ruins -- tCoda: After Extinctualism: Hope for Life -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRomantic Revelations shows that the nonhuman is fundamental to Romanticism’s political responses to climatic catastrophes. Exploring what he calls "post-apocalyptic Romanticism," Chris Washington intervenes in the critical conversation that has long defined Romanticism as an apocalyptic field. "Apocalypse" means "the revelation of a perfected world," which sees Romanticism’s back-to-nature environmentalism as a return to paradise and peace on earth. Romantic Revelations, however, demonstrates that the destructive climate change events of 1816, "the year without a summer," changed Romantic thinking about the environment and the end of the world. Their post-apocalyptic visions correlate to the beginning of the Anthropocene, the time when humans initiated the possible extinction of their own species and potentially the earth. Rather than constructing paradises where humans are reborn or human existence ends, the later Romantics are interested in how to survive in the ashes after great social and climatic global disasters. Romantic Revelations argues that Percy Shelley, Mary Shelley, Lord Byron, John Clare, and Jane Austen sketch out a post-apocalyptic world that, in contrast to the sunnier Romantic narratives, is paradoxically the vision that offers us hope. In thinking through life after disaster, Washington contends that these authors craft an optimistic vision of the future that leads to a new politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aApocalyptic literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEnd of the world in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 18th Century .2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aFrankenstein.  aJane Austen.  aLord Byron.  aMary Shelley.  aPercy Shelley.  aRomanticism.  aapocalypse.  aclimate change.  aenvironmental history.  ahistory of literature.  aliterary criticism.  apost-apocalyptic Romanticism.  apost-apocalyptic literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz9